<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-16T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-16T20:00:00-05:00" n="309" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d309">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 658.119/158</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-16T20:00:00-05:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">January 16, 1918, 8 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>6274. Following for <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> from War Trade Board:</p>
                            <p>Our No. 17. Your 8242. We wish to impress upon you that the licensing
                                for Sweden of commodities in quantities suggested pending final
                                agreement is contrary to policy approved by British and continuously
                                followed heretofore by this Board. Also that it will be considered
                                by other northern neutrals as discriminating in Sweden’s favor and
                                will probably make all our negotiations more difficult. If after
                                weighing these disadvantages Allied representatives feel the
                                concession necessary we authorize you to make the arrangement.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>